               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000064b-1" xml:lang="en">Dajue liushi Hall (大覺六師殿), now destroyed, was the second major <term>timber-frame</term> structure on the central axis of <placeName ref="/keyword/000064">Longxing Monastery</placeName>. Originally built during the <term ref="/keyword/k000074">Northern Song dynasty</term>'s Yuanfeng reign period (1078-1085 CE), it suffered extensive damage in the early 20th century and was beyond repair by the time Liang Sicheng had visited in 1933.</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000064b-1" xml:lang="en">Archaeological evidence suggests that the hall was nine bays wide and six bays deep, with a width of 53 meters and a depth of 35 meters, which made it the largest building in the complex. The hall was dedicated to the historical Buddha, Shakyamuni, and the six Buddhas that predated him—Vipaśyin, Śikhin, Viśvabhu, Krakucchanda, Kanakamuni, and Kāśyapa.</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000064b-1" xml:lang="zh-Hant">大覺六師殿為<placeName ref="/keyword/000064">隆興寺</placeName>中軸線上第二座主要木構建築。此殿始建於<term ref="/keyword/k000074">北宋</term>元豐年間（1078-1085）。但在民國 （b. 1912) 初年，梁思成探訪此址時已毀壞坍塌。</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000064b-1" xml:lang="zh-Hant">大覺六師殿為<term>單檐</term><term subtype="keyword" ref="/keyword/k000143">歇山</term>頂建築，面闊九間，寬53米，進深六間，深35米，曾為隆興寺建築群中面積最大的建築。其中供奉釋迦摩尼佛以及釋迦摩尼佛以前的六佛像，即毗婆師佛、屍棄佛、毗舍浮佛、拘留孫佛、拘那舍牟尼佛、迦葉佛像。</p>
               </desc>
